An author like Giraldus, whose life had been chequered by such varied soenes, who had frequently visited Paris and Rome, had studied for years in both cities, had been employed in negotiations of the most delicate nature, and enjoyed the most intimate acquaintance with contempo- rary statesmen and prelates, in penning a work like the present, and reviewing the soenes of his past life, could scarcely fail of committing to paper events and anecdotos interesting to the general mador, and most important to the scholar employed in historical investigatione.

Itis then no matter of surprise, that the publication

of the work' should have been anxiously expected
